'''Lusia "Lucy" Harris-Stewart''' (born '''Lusia Harris'''; February 10, 1955) is a former [[United States|American]] [[basketball]] player. Harris is considered to be one of the pioneers of [[women's basketball]]. She played for [[Delta State University]] and won three consecutive [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (AIAW) [[AIAW Women's Basketball Tournament|National Championships]], the predecessors to the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) championships, from 1975 to 1977. In international level, she represented the [[United States women's national basketball team|United States' national team]] and won the [[silver medal]] in the [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Olympic Games]], the first ever women's [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|basketball tournament in the Olympic Games]]. She played professional basketball with the [[Houston Angels]] of the [[Women's Professional Basketball League]] (WBL) and was the first and only woman ever officially [[Draft (sports)|drafted]] by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), a men's professional basketball league. For her achievements, Harris has been inducted to the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]] and [[Women's Basketball Hall of Fame]].

==Early life==
Harris was born in [[Minter City, Mississippi]] to Ethel and Willie Harris, a vegetable farmer. She is the tenth of eleven children and the fourth of five daughters. All of her brothers and one of her older sisters, Janie, also played basketball.<ref name="interview">{{cite web|url=http://digilib.usm.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/coh&CISOPTR=3087&REC=3|title=Oral history with Ms. Lusia Harris-Stewart|date=December, 18 1999|publisher=University of Southern Mississippi|accessdate=August 31, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5sLD9bLuU|archivedate=August 29, 2010}}</ref> Harris and her siblings attended Amanda Elzy High School in [[Greenwood, Mississippi]].<ref name="interview"/>

Harris played basketball under coach Conway Stewart in high school. She won the [[most valuable player]] award three consecutive years, served as team captain and made the state All-Star team.<ref name="porter">{{cite book|title=Basketball: A Biographical Dictionary|first=David L.|last=Porter|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2005|isbn=9780313309526|pages=454<U+2013>455|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WRw2DRCjHuoC&dq=isbn:9780313309526&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> She scored a school record 46 points in one game and led her school to the state tournament in [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref name="wsf">{{cite web|url=http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/Content/Articles/Athletes/About-Athletes/L/Lucys-Legacy-A-Profile-of-Lusia-HarrisStewart.aspx|title=Lucy's Legacy: A Profile of Lusia Harris-Stewart|first=Helen|last=Wheelock|publisher=Women's Sports Foundation|accessdate=August 31, 2010|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20081121054040/http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/Content/Articles/Athletes/About-Athletes/L/Lucys-Legacy-A-Profile-of-Lusia-HarrisStewart.aspx|archivedate=November 21, 2008}}</ref>

After her high school graduation, she planned to attend [[Alcorn State University]], which did not have a women's basketball team.<ref name="lannin">{{cite book|title=A History of Basketball for Girls and Women: From Bloomers to Big Leagues|first=Joanne|last=Lannin|year=2000|publisher=Lerner Sports|isbn=9780822598633|pages=84<U+2013>85}}</ref> However, she was asked by Melvin Hemphill, the recruiter for coach [[Margaret Wade (basketball coach)|Margaret Wade]], who was restarting a collegiate women's team, if she would attend [[Delta State University]] in [[Cleveland, Mississippi]].<ref name="grundy">{{cite book|title=Shattering The Glass: The Remarkable History of Women's Basketball|first=Pamela|last=Grundy|coauthors=Shackelford, Susan|year=2005|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9781565848221|pages=163<U+2013>168|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZfS_3MUPBXoC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> This was before [[Title IX]], so there were no sports scholarships for women. She attended school on a combination of academic [[scholarship]]s and [[Cooperative education|work study]] funds.<ref name="lannin"/>

==College career==
In her first year in Delta State, Harris helped the Lady Statesmen to a 16<U+2013>2 record. However, they finished third in the regional tournament and failed to qualify to the national tournament.<ref name="mediaguide">{{cite web|url=http://www.gostatesmen.com/documents/2010/10/14/History_and_Records.pdf|title=2010<U+2013>2011 Delta State University Lady Statesmen Basketball Guide, Section 5: The History|format=PDF|publisher=Delta State University|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref> The following year, the Lady Statesmen qualified to the national tournament at [[Harrisonburg, Virginia]]. They went all the way to the final where they met the Mighty Macs of [[Immaculata University]] who had won the last three consecutive AIAW championships.<ref name="williamson">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090540/index.htm|title=The Women|first=Nancy|last=Williamson|date=December 1, 1975|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Warner Company|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> In the final, Harris scored 32 points and recorded 16 rebounds to led Delta State past Immaculata 90<U+2013>81.<ref name="1975final">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pd9NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EosDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2675,3058390|title=Delta State dethrones Immaculata|date=March 24, 1975|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|location=Fredericksburg, Virginia|publisher=The Free Lance<U+2013>Star Publishing Company|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref> The 1975 championship game was televised nationally (albeit delayed). This is the first year that women's basketball games were nationally televised by a major network.<ref name="lannin"/> That season, Delta State went undefeated in with a 28<U+2013>0 record, the only undefeated college season that year (men or women).<ref name="williamson"/> Harris scored a total of 138 points and 63 rebounds in four games at the national tournament and was named as the tournament's [[most valuable player]].<ref name="1975final"/>

In the 1975<U+2013>76 season, Delta State and Immaculata met again in the national tournament final. Harris again led Delta State with 30 points and 18 rebounds in a 69<U+2013>64 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jKheAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x1MNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5666,5674050|title=Lucia Harris, Delta State will get better|date=March 29, 1976|newspaper=St. Joseph News-Press|location=Saint Joseph, Missouri|publisher=News-Press & Gazette Company|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref> That season, she led the nation in scoring with 1,060 points and a 31.2 points per game average, including a 58-point game against [[Tennessee Technological University|Tennessee Tech]]. In her senior season, Delta State played a game in the [[Madison Square Garden]], in which Harris scored 47 points. This was one of the first women's basketball game ever played there.<ref name="porter"/> Delta State then went to the national tournament final for the third year in a row. In the final, Harris scored 23 points and recorded 16 rebounds as Delta State defeated [[Louisiana State University]] 68<U+2013>55 for their third consecutive title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wYclAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MPUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2921,1368638|title=Delta State take 3rd title|date=March 29, 1977|newspaper=Washington Afro-American|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Afro-American Co|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>

Harris was named as the national tournament's [[most valuable player]] and to the [[All-America]]n first team during Delta State's three winning seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbhof.com/harris.html|title=Lusia Harris-Stewart Bio|publisher=Women's Basketball Hall of Fame|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name="mediaguide"/> Her college career record was 109<U+2013>6, and included victories over later [[NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Division I]] powerhouses such as Immaculata University, [[University of Tennessee]], [[Baylor University]], [[University of Mississippi]], Louisiana State University and [[Louisiana Tech University]].<ref name="mediaguide"/> Harris finished her college career with 2,981 points and 1,662 rebounds, averaging 25.9 points and 14.5 rebounds per game.<ref name="mediaguide"/> She also graduated with fifteen of eighteen Delta State's team, single game, and career records. In 1977, she won the inaugural [[Honda Sports Award]] for basketball,<ref name="Honda Sports Award">{{cite web|title=Past Honda Sports Award Winners|url=http://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/past_honda_award_winners.html|publisher=Collegiate Women Sports Awards|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref> as well as the [[Honda-Broderick Cup|Broderick Cup]], an award for outstanding female athletes in college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/hall-of-famers/tag/lusia-harris-stewart|title=Lusia Harris-Stewart Bio|publisher=Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref>

==National team career==
{{MedalTableTop}}
{{MedalCountry|{{USA}}}}
{{MedalSport|Women's [[basketball]]}}
{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}
{{MedalGold|[[1975 Pan American Games|1975 Mexico City]]|[[Basketball at the 1975 Pan American Games|Team competition]]}}
{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}
{{MedalSilver|[[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]]|[[Basketball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Team competition]]}}
{{MedalBottom}}
In 1975, Harris was selected to represent the [[United States women's national basketball team|United States' national team]] in the [[1975 FIBA World Championship for Women|FIBA World Championship for Women]] in [[Colombia]] and the [[1975 Pan American Games|Pan American Games]] in [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]]. She teamed up with high school star [[Nancy Lieberman]] and fellow college stars [[Ann Meyers]] and [[Pat Summitt|Pat Head]]. In the FIBA World Championship, the United States compiled a 4<U+2013>3 record and finished in eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/womens/national/wwc_1975.html|title=Seventh World Championship for Women <U+2013> 1975|publisher=USA Basketball|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> In the Pan American Games, the United States team went unbeaten in seven games to win the [[gold medal]], their first win since [[1963 Pan American Games|1963]]. They averaged 86.7 points per game with an average winning margin of 34.4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/womens/panamerican/wpag_1975.html|title=Seventh Pan American Games <U+2013> 1975|publisher=USA Basketball|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref>

The following year, Harris was selected to represent the United States in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]], [[Canada]], the first ever women's [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|basketball tournament in the Olympic Games]]. She teamed up with most of her teammates in the 1975 Pan American Games, including Lieberman, Meyers and Head. In the opening game against [[Japan women's national basketball team|Japan]], Harris scored the first ever points in women's Olympic basketball tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Fc48AAAAIBAJ&sjid=6S0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=2322,1011673|title=First-ever women's cage action today|date=July 19, 1976|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|publisher=Bangor Publishing Company|location=Bangor, Maine|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name="porter"/> The United States team won three games and lost two games against [[Japan women's national basketball team|Japan]] and the [[Soviet Union women's national basketball team|Soviet Union]]. The Soviet Union team went undefeated and won the gold medal, while the United States team won the [[silver medal]]. Harris played in all five games, averaging 15.2 points and 7.0 rebounds per game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/womens/national/woly_1976.html|title=Games of the XXIst Olympiad <U+2013> 1976|publisher=USA Basketball|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref>

==Professional career==
In the seventh round of the [[1977 NBA Draft]], the [[Utah Jazz|New Orleans Jazz]] selected Harris with the 137th pick overall. She became the second woman ever drafted by an NBA team, after Denise Long, who was selected by the [[Golden State Warriors|San Francisco Warriors]] in the [[1969 NBA Draft|1969 Draft]].<ref name="oddities">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/draft2003/draft_oddities_030619.html|title=Draft Oddities|first=Randy|last=Kim|date=June 19, 2003|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref> However, the league voided the Warriors' selection, thus Harris became the first and only woman ever officially drafted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-02-10/sports/sp-3529_1_denise-long|title=Denise Long, the Patron Saint of Girls Basketball, Is Now 33|first=Kevin|last=Simpson|date=February 10, 1985|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Interactive, Inc|accessdate=August 25, 2010}}</ref> Harris did not express an interest to play in the NBA and declined to try out for the Jazz.<ref name="kporter">{{cite book|title=Mad seasons: the story of the first Women's Professional Basketball League, 1978<U+2013>1981|first=Kara|last=Porter|year=2006|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=9780803287891|page=157|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2pVr1zQmF64C&pg=PA157&lpg=PA157#v=onepage&q=lusia&f=false|accessdate=August 25, 2010}}</ref> It was later revealed that she was pregnant at the time, which made her unable to attend the Jazz's training camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/poker/ci_12649320|title=NBA draft: Jazz draft woman in '77|first=Steve|last=Luhm|date=June 20, 2009|work=El Paso Times|publisher=MediaNews Group|accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref> She was selected ahead of 33 other male players, including the Jazz's eighth round selection, Dave Speicher from the [[University of Toledo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1977.html|title=1977 NBA Draft|work=basketball-reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref>

Harris never played in the NBA or any other men's basketball league but played professional basketball briefly in the 1979<U+2013>80 season with the [[Houston Angels]] of the [[Women's Professional Basketball League]] (WBL).<ref name="kporter"/> She was initially picked as the number one free agent by the Angels in 1978, the league's inaugural season.<ref name="porter"/>

==Personal life==
Harris graduated from Delta State with a Bachelor's degree in health, physical education and recreation in 1977.<ref name="porter"/> After graduation, she worked for Delta State as an admissions counselor and assistant basketball coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gostatesmen.com/news/2009/6/12/WBB_0612094720.aspx|title=Former Lady Statesmen Lusia Harris-Stewart featured in Women's Hoops Pioneers|first=Chris|last=Maynard|date=June 12, 2009|publisher=Delta State University|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> She earned a Master's degree in education from Delta State in 1984. After leaving the assistant coaching post in Delta State, she served as the head coach at [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston]] for two years.<ref name="interview"/> She then returned to her native Mississippi and became a high school teacher and coach. Harris married George E. Stewart on February 4, 1977.<ref name="porter"/> They have four children, two sons and a pair of twin daughters.<ref name="interview"/>

==Legacy==
For her achievements and contributions to the Delta State University, Harris was inducted to the Delta State's Hall of Fame in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gostatesmen.com/hof.aspx?hof=31&path=&kiosk=|title=Lusia Harris-Stewart Bio|publisher=Delta State University|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> In 1992, Harris and former player [[Nera White]] became the first two women ever inducted to the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/12/sports/basketball-9-lifetimes-of-memories-wander-into-hall-of-fame.html|title=9 Lifetimes of Memories Wander Into Hall of Fame|first=Malcolm|last=Moran|date=May 12, 1992|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> She also became the first African-American woman inductee.<ref name="cavs">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/cavaliers/news/lbj_lusia_harris_stewat_070226.html|title=Women<U+2019>s Basketball Legend Lusia Harris-Stewart To Be Honored Tuesday Night|date=February 26, 2007|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|accessdate=August 31, 2010|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101203064349/http://www.nba.com/cavaliers/news/lbj_lusia_harris_stewat_070226.html|archivedate=December 3, 2010}}</ref> In 1998, Harris, along with her college coach, [[Margaret Wade (basketball coach)|Margaret Wade]], and her teammates in the [[United States women's national basketball team|national team]], [[Nancy Lieberman]], [[Ann Meyers]] and [[Pat Summitt|Pat Head]], were named among the 26 inaugural inductees to the [[Women's Basketball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/16/sports/basketball-college-women-women-s-hall-of-fame-conradt-leads-26-inductees.html|title=Conradt Leads 26 Inductees|date=November 16, 1998|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> She has also been named to the International Women's Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name="wsf"/>

